# THE PROJECT BRIEF #

# Project Name #
INTELLIGENT SMART CITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM


# Product Description / Presentation #

INTELLIGENT SMART CITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM


Build Brief â€¢ Claude-Optimized â€¢ Production-Ready

Product description / presentation
CivitasIQ is a unified, AI-driven command platform for modern cities. It fuses live sensor data, geospatial feeds, and citizen inputs into a real-time city twin that forecasts demand, flags anomalies, and coordinates response across mobility, energy, water, waste, and public safety. Teams get an operational picture, automated alerts, what-if simulations, and agent-assisted actions.

Why people/teams love it:
â€¢ One pane of glass for all city operations (traffic, transit, utilities, incidents, permits).
â€¢ Real-time insights with explainable forecasts and policy-grounded recommendations.
â€¢ Digital-twin interactions: simulate road closures, reroute transit, re-time signals, adjust energy loads.
â€¢ Agentic co-pilots: research policy constraints, summarize incidents, draft stakeholder updates, generate SOP checklists.
â€¢ Built for trust: audit trails, RBAC, data lineage, and human-in-the-loop approvals.
Framework choice & why
â€¢ Orchestration: LangGraph on top of LangChain â€” deterministic, stateful multi-agent flows (ingestion â†’ quality â†’ forecast â†’ recommend â†’ approve â†’ act) with checkpointing and human approval gates.
â€¢ Retrieval: RAG over municipal policies, contracts, SOPs, vendor manuals using pgvector; provenance and timestamps enforced.
â€¢ GenAI: OpenAI + Anthropic for summarization, reasoning, multilingual comms; structured JSON outputs for safe automation.
â€¢ Core stack (fixed by spec): Next.js 14 (App Router), FastAPI (async), PostgreSQL (+PostGIS, TimescaleDB, pgvector), Redis (cache/queues), Vercel + Render.
1. BACKEND ARCHITECTURE (extensive)
â€¢ FastAPI (async) service layout: /apps/{domain} (mobility, utilities, safety, permits), /core (auth, users, tenants, RBAC), /ai (agents, RAG, models).
â€¢ Domain micro-modules with routers: mobility.traffic, mobility.transit, utilities.energy, utilities.water, safety.incidents, citizen.feedback.
â€¢ API styles: REST for CRUD/config; WebSockets for live channels (/ws/alerts, /ws/telemetry, /ws/command); background jobs for heavy compute.
â€¢ Data ingestion adapters:
â€¢   â€¢ MQTT/HTTP for IoT gateways (air quality, parking, meters) with TLS + mTLS option.
â€¢   â€¢ GTFS-Realtime (transit), traffic loop counters, signal controllers (NTCIP), bike/scooter APIs.
â€¢   â€¢ CAD/911 incident feed (secured), weather APIs, utility SCADA via OPC-UA proxy (read-only).
â€¢   â€¢ Camera edge inferencing hook (optional) via RTSP â†’ edge gateway â†’ event counts (no PII payloads).
â€¢ Event pipeline:
â€¢   â€¢ Write-ahead raw_events table â†’ streaming normalizer â†’ feature enricher (geo, hour-of-day, weather join) â†’ facts tables.
â€¢   â€¢ Optional Kafka/Redpanda for high-throughput fan-out; Redis Streams as lightweight alternative.
â€¢ PostgreSQL extensions: PostGIS (geospatial), TimescaleDB (time-series), pgvector (RAG & similarity).
â€¢ Schema highlights:
â€¢   â€¢ core.users, core.tenants, core.roles, core.audit_logs
â€¢   â€¢ geo.assets(id, type, geom, meta), geo.zones(id, name, polygon, rules)
â€¢   â€¢ ts.telemetry(asset_id, ts, metrics jsonb, tags jsonb, location geography(Point)) (hypertable)
â€¢   â€¢ ops.incidents(id, source, status, severity, geom, started_at, resolved_at, links jsonb)
â€¢   â€¢ ops.recommendations(id, incident_id?, type, payload jsonb, rationale, confidence, created_at)
â€¢   â€¢ rag.documents(id, tenant_id, source_uri, title, text, metadata jsonb, embedding vector)
â€¢   â€¢ mobility.signals(id, controller_ref, phase_plan jsonb), mobility.travel_times(corridor_id, ts, minutes)
â€¢ Caching & queues: Redis (keys: session:*, cache:*, queue:*). Prefer Redis RQ/Arq workers for: model inference batches, ETL, exports.
â€¢ AI services (FastAPI subapp /ai):
â€¢   â€¢ RAG pipeline: loader â†’ chunker (policy-aware) â†’ embed â†’ store (pgvector) â†’ cite & quote spans in responses.
â€¢   â€¢ Forecasting service: demand (transit ridership), traffic volume, energy load, water usage (Prophet/Neural forecasting behind API).
â€¢   â€¢ Optimization: signal timing suggestion, plow/collection routing (heuristics + constraints) output as JSON ops.
â€¢   â€¢ Agents via LangGraph: Data Quality Agent, Policy Compliance Agent, Incident Summarizer, Recommender, Notifier.
â€¢ Digital Twin service: entity graph of assets/links/states with scenario sandbox (what-if write set kept separate).
â€¢ Security & auth: JWT (access/refresh), tenant scoping, RBAC (roleâ†’permission matrix), IP allowlists for admin APIs.
â€¢ Auditing & lineage: all AI outputs stored with inputs, prompt hash, model, embeddings, source doc IDs, and user approver.
â€¢ File/Blob storage: S3-compatible (minio/AWS) for documents, exports, tiles; signed URLs via backend.
â€¢ Geospatial utilities: isochrones, snapping, geofencing enter/exit triggers; map tile generation job (mbtiles).
â€¢ Rate limiting & quotas: per-tenant, per-route; burst + sustained with sliding window in Redis.
â€¢ Internationalization: backend locale middleware; time zone normalization (UTC storage, client zone render).
â€¢ Deployment profiles: dev (sqlite for local), staging/prod (Postgres), migrations via Alembic with PostGIS/Timescale enable scripts.
2. FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE
â€¢ Next.js 14 App Router with feature folders: /(dashboard)/(mobility)/(utilities)/(safety)/admin.
â€¢ State/data: React Query (server state), Zustand (local UI), URL-as-state for filters; optimistic UI for config changes.
â€¢ Real-time: WebSocket hook useLiveChannel(topic) with backoff + presence; toasts for alerts; activity ticker.
â€¢ Geospatial UI: Mapbox GL JS layer manager (heatmaps, choropleths, incidents, isochrones), deck.gl optional for large layers.
â€¢ Charts: Recharts/Victory for time-series; virtualized tables for telemetry and incidents.
â€¢ Workflows: incident triage drawer, recommendation review modal (explanations, citations), one-click actions with approval.
â€¢ Scenario Studio: side-by-side compare (baseline vs proposed), sandbox commit with diff summary.
â€¢ Admin: user/role manager, data source configs, API keys, quotas, webhook destinations.
â€¢ Design system: Tailwind + shadcn/ui components; tokens for light/dark + high-contrast; LTR/RTL support.
â€¢ Accessibility: keyboard-first navigation, screen-reader labels, live region updates for alerts.
â€¢ Internationalization: next-intl; numeral/date localization; unit toggles (imperial/metric).
â€¢ File flows: drag-drop for policy PDFs/CSVs/GeoJSON with progress; inline validation and data dictionaries.
â€¢ Offline/Resilience: SW caching of static assets; request replay for minor outages (non-critical ops).
3. DESIGN REQUIREMENTS (UI/UX)
â€¢ Operational clarity: status-first layouts, color-safe severities, dense tables with row focus mode.
â€¢ Geospatial-first: map as primary canvas with dockable panels; responsive to kiosk, tablet, desktop.
â€¢ Progressive disclosure: overview â†’ drilldown â†’ action; breadcrumbs & timeline scrubber for incidents.
â€¢ Micro-interactions: hover states reveal KPIs and trend sparklines; skeleton loaders for streaming tiles.
â€¢ Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 AA (contrast â‰¥ 4.5:1, focus rings, captions on videos, live region announcements).
â€¢ Branding: city theming (logo, colors) via CSS variables; emergency mode theme with high-contrast palette.
4. CORE INTEGRATIONS
â€¢ OpenAI & Anthropic (LLM): summarization, recommendations, multilingual communications; JSON-mode outputs.
â€¢ Map & Geo: Mapbox, PostGIS, GeoJSON import/export; optional ESRI Feature Service connector.
â€¢ Transit & Mobility: GTFS/GTFS-RT, signal controllers (NTCIP), connected vehicle feeds (read-only).
â€¢ Utilities: OPC-UA proxy (read), smart meter batch imports (CSV/Parquet), energy market pricing APIs (read).
â€¢ Messaging: Redis Streams (baseline) or Kafka/Redpanda (high-throughput).
â€¢ Storage: S3-compatible object store for docs/tiles/exports.
â€¢ Auth: SSO via SAML/OIDC (Azure AD, Okta).
â€¢ Notifications: SMTP/SendGrid; webhooks (Teams/Slack) with templated payloads.
5. DELIVERABLES REQUIRED
â€¢ Next.js 14 frontend with TypeScript/Tailwind, role-based dashboards, map & charts, real-time alerts UI.
â€¢ FastAPI backend (async) with domain routers, WebSockets, workers, and documented OpenAPI.
â€¢ PostgreSQL schema with PostGIS, TimescaleDB hypertables, and pgvector stores; Alembic migrations.
â€¢ RAG pipeline over policy/SOP documents with citation UI and evidence storage.
â€¢ Forecasting & optimization services with APIs and scenario endpoints.
â€¢ File ingestion pipelines (CSV/GeoJSON/PDF) with validation and lineage.
â€¢ Email/webhook notification system with templates and throttling.
â€¢ IaC-ready deployment configs for Vercel (FE) and Render (BE); env var matrix.
â€¢ Comprehensive docs (runbooks, API, data dictionary) and onboarding sample dataset.
6. SUCCESS CRITERIA
â€¢ Unified operational picture updates in near real-time (<5s p95 from ingest to UI for standard topics).
â€¢ Explainable recommendations with linked citations and confidence scoring for all AI outputs.
â€¢ City-scale geospatial layers render at 60fps on modern desktops, 30fps on tablets (typical datasets).
â€¢ No critical actions applied without human approval; all automations are reversible with audit logs.
â€¢ Multi-tenant isolation verified; RBAC enforced on every route and WebSocket topic.
7. IMPLEMENTATION GUIDELINES
â€¢ Type safety end-to-end: Pydantic v2 schemas â†” TypeScript types (openapi-typescript generation).
â€¢ Consistent IDs/keys: UUIDv7 for entities; ULIDs acceptable for telemetry partitions.
â€¢ Idempotency: POST actions include idempotency keys; exporters deduplicate by content hash.
â€¢ Prompts as code: store system & task prompts in repo with versions; include tests and linting.
â€¢ RAG hygiene: chunk by structure (headings/tables), store source offsets; block responses without sources for policy Q&A.
â€¢ Geospatial best practices: store geometry in SRID 4326; index with GIST; avoid large payloads to client (tiling/gzip).
â€¢ Background work: offload heavy compute to workers; use backpressure signals on ingestion.
â€¢ WebSocket etiquette: small deltas, heartbeat/ping, resumable cursor for streams.
â€¢ Docs-first APIs: keep OpenAPI in sync; include examples and error models; paginate consistently.
8. SECURITY & COMPLIANCE
â€¢ Data classification: public / internal / restricted; PII minimization; no biometric/face payloads stored.
â€¢ Encryption: TLS 1.2+ in transit; AES-256 at rest (DB & object storage); KMS-managed keys; envelope encryption for secrets.
â€¢ RBAC & tenancy: per-tenant schemas or row-level security; JWT with short TTL; refresh + rotation; device/session revocation.
â€¢ Audit & lineage: append-only logs for admin & AI actions; prompt/response archival with hashes and source IDs.
â€¢ Model safety: content filters; jailbreak protection; output moderation; explicit disclaimers for non-binding recommendations.
â€¢ Compliance alignment: ISO 27001/SOC 2 controls; GDPR/CCPA data rights; CJIS-compatible mode for public safety tenants.
â€¢ Supply chain: pin images; verify checksums; SBOM generation; dependency scanning; signed container images.
â€¢ Incident response: playbooks, on-call runbooks, webhooks to paging tools; forensics-ready log retention.
Claude â€” 5 critical prompts (builds on prebuilt repo)
PROMPT 1 â€” PROJECT SETUP & ARCHITECTURE (use existing scaffold)
Assume the monorepo is already initialized with Next.js 14 (App Router), FastAPI (async), Postgres (+PostGIS, TimescaleDB, pgvector), Redis, and LangGraph/LangChain. Do NOT change the stack. Generate only new/modified files as unified patches. Add Alembic migrations to enable PostGIS, TimescaleDB, and vector indexes; create schemas core, geo, ts, ops, rag. Output: file tree + patches + env.sample updates.
PROMPT 2 â€” CORE BACKEND IMPLEMENTATION (routers, models, ws, workers)
Within /backend, implement domain routers (mobility, utilities, safety), Pydantic schemas, and CRUD. Add WebSocket topics /ws/alerts and /ws/telemetry with heartbeat and replay cursors. Implement Redis RQ/Arq workers for ETL, forecasting, and exports. Create RAG service endpoints (/ai/ask, /ai/search) with citation returns. Output: code diffs, OpenAPI excerpt, and curl examples.
PROMPT 3 â€” FRONTEND COMPONENTS & UI (dashboards, map, real-time)
Within /frontend, implement dashboards and a Mapbox layer manager. Create hooks useLiveChannel and useScenarioSandbox. Build IncidentTriageDrawer and RecommendationReviewModal with citation side panel. Ensure a11y attributes and keyboard flows. Output: file diffs, route map, and demo seed data JSON.
PROMPT 4 â€” AI INTEGRATION & FEATURES (LangGraph agents, RAG, forecasts)
Implement LangGraph agents: DataQualityAgent, PolicyComplianceAgent, IncidentSummarizer, Recommender. Wire RAG over /rag.documents with quote spans and confidence. Wrap forecasting (traffic/energy/water) behind /ai/forecast endpoints. All outputs must be structured JSON with rationale and confidence. Provide prompt templates as code.
PROMPT 5 â€” DEPLOYMENT & OPTIMIZATION (configs, seeds, idempotency)
Provide Vercel (FE) and Render (BE) configs, Dockerfiles, and Procfiles. Add seed scripts for demo city data, role templates, and sample documents. Implement idempotency keys, rate limiting, and signed URLs. Output: deployment steps and .env matrices.




